  <li id="comment-41280" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/01628880208157866153" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">jerbear</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2014/01/a-good-person-to-know/#comment-41280"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2014-01-12T03:39:39-05:00">Sunday, January 12, 2014 at 3:39 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Hello! I&#39;ve been reading your blog for a couple of years now and have never commented- I love it.</p>
<p>For whatever reason, this post of all posts made me want to comment. I have a love&#8211;meh relationship with oatmeal but when the pendulum swings towards love, I also, as some of the earlier commenters reported, use the overnight method. I basically soak the steel cut oats in a bunch of water (I don&#39;t measure). Then in the morning, I pour off the excess water, add mostly milk to cover the oats by a bit, bring to a boil, and turn off the heat and let it sit for 5-10 minutes. I started doing this to reduce the amount of time it takes the oats to cook, and also to prevent the oats from scorching (less time with the heat on, less chance of me walking away and not stirring it). Yea oatmeal! </p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
